  "prompt": "What is thermal inversion?",
  "response": "Thermal inversion, also known as temperature inversion, is a meteorological phenomenon where a layer of warm air temporarily sits on top of a layer of cooler air near the Earth's surface, contrary to the normal vertical temperature gradient. In a typical atmospheric condition, air temperature decreases with increasing altitude. During a thermal inversion, this pattern is reversed, creating a stable layer that can trap pollutants and cause several environmental and health effects:\n\n1. Characteristics:\n- Warm air layer sits above cooler air\n- Prevents normal vertical air mixing\n- Creates a \"lid\" effect in the atmosphere\n\n2. Causes:\n- Nighttime cooling of ground surface\n- Cold air sinking into valleys\n- High-pressure weather systems\n- Urban heat island effects\n\n3. Environmental impacts:\n- Traps air pollutants close to the ground\n- Reduces air quality\n- Can lead to smog formation\n- Increases respiratory health risks\n\n4. Common locations:\n- Mountain valleys\n- Urban areas\n- Coastal regions\n- Industrial zones\n\n5. Potential consequences:\n- Reduced visibility\n- Increased air pollution concentration\n- Higher risk of respiratory problems\n- Potential negative effects on vegetation and wildlife\n\nUnderstanding thermal inversions helps meteorologists and environmental scientists monitor and predict air quality conditions.",
